🔹 Worker Threads
Introduced to handle CPU-intensive tasks using multithreading.
Runs multiple threads inside a single process.
Threads share memory (can use SharedArrayBuffer), making communication faster.
Best for:
Heavy computations (image processing, ML tasks)
Avoiding blocking the event loop

👉 Key point: Parallelism within the same process

🔹 Clustering (cluster module)
Used to scale Node.js apps across multiple CPU cores.
Creates multiple processes (workers) that share the same server port.
Each worker runs its own event loop and memory space.
A master process distributes incoming requests.

Best for:

Web servers handling high traffic
Horizontal scaling on a single machine

👉 Key point: Multiple processes handling requests in parallel

🔹 Forking (child_process.fork)
Creates a new Node.js process.
Used for running independent tasks or services.
Communication happens via IPC (message passing).
No shared memory by default.

Best for:

Background jobs
Isolated task execution



API Debugging Strategy – Small Notes (Interview Quick Revision)
1. Some Users Slow, Others Fine
Check:
User data size
Cache miss
Region/location
Premium feature path
User-specific locks
Payload difference
Strategy:

Compare slow user vs fast user using logs/traces.

2. All Users Slow
Check:
Traffic spike
DB pool exhaustion
Cache outage
Dependency slow
Thread starvation
Recent deploy
Strategy:

Check shared bottlenecks + rollback if recent release.

3. CPU Normal but API Slow
Check:
Waiting on DB
Locks
External API
DNS/network
Thread queues
Strategy:

CPU ≠ healthy. Inspect waits/blocking.

4. DB Healthy but API Slow
Check:
Connection pool full
Slow query
ORM N+1
Retry storms
Network latency
Strategy:

DB health ≠ query/path health.

5. Memory Fine but Slow
Check:
GC pauses
Memory leak
Heap pressure
Object churn
Strategy:

Look at GC logs / heap metrics.

6. p50 Good, p99 Bad
Check:
One slow pod
One shard slow
Retries
Cold cache
GC spikes
Strategy:

Investigate outliers, not averages.

7. Errors Zero but Users Say Slow
Check:
High latency
Client timeout near misses
Retries hidden
Strategy:

Look at p95/p99 latency.

8. Only Write APIs Slow
Check:
Row locks
Transactions
Hot rows
Sync downstream calls
Strategy:

Inspect lock waits + write path.

9. Only Read APIs Slow
Check:
Missing indexes
Full scans
Cache miss storm
Heavy joins
Strategy:

Check query plans + cache ratio.

10. One Pod Slow
Check:
Bad node
Memory leak
CPU throttling
Stale connections
Strategy:

Compare pod metrics, restart pod if needed.

11. One Region Slow
Check:
CDN issue
DNS routing
Regional LB
Replica lag
Strategy:

Compare region dashboards.

12. After Deployment Slow
Check:
Code regression
Config change
New SQL
Pool size changed
Strategy:

Rollback first, RCA later.

13. Worked in QA, Broke in Prod
Check:
Large prod data
Real traffic concurrency
Dirty data
Config mismatch
Real dependency latency
Strategy:

QA validates function, prod validates scale.

14. Every Hour Slowdown
Check:
Cron jobs
Backups
ETL
Cache refresh
Strategy:

Correlate with schedule.

15. Queue Growing
Check:
Slow consumers
Poison messages
Retry loops
Dependency delays
Strategy:

Compare producer vs consumer throughput.

16. Cache Healthy but Slow
Check:
Low hit ratio
Hot key
Huge payload
Stampede
Strategy:

Health up ≠ useful cache.

17. External Dependency Slow
Check:
Payment API
Auth service
CRM/search service
Strategy:

Timeout + fallback + circuit breaker.

18. Traffic Same but Latency Doubled
Check:
Cache drop
Query plan changed
Dependency slower
New deployment
Strategy:

Efficiency dropped, not traffic issue.

19. Sudden Spike in DB CPU
Check:
Missing index
Full scans
Cache down
Burst traffic
Strategy:

Check top queries immediately.

20. Login API Slow Only
Check:
Auth provider
Token signing
Session store
User profile fetch
Strategy:

Trace auth chain.